{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"44f00be6-c121-48d1-a333-d281ad828fd4","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, so I'll give you the commands to run on your server.\n\n## 1. Determine the runtime\n\nRun these on your Linux box:\n\n```bash\n# Check for CoreCLR — if libcoreclr.so is loaded, it's CoreCLR\ngrep -q 'libcoreclr\\.so' /proc/12345/maps && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Not CoreCLR\"\n\n# Check for NativeAOT — no libcoreclr.so, but the binary is self-contained\n# NativeAOT apps are single static binaries with no JIT\nreadlink /proc/12345/exe\nfile $(readlink /proc/12345/exe)  # NativeAOT will show \"statically linked\" or no libcoreclr dependency\nldd $(readlink /proc/12345/exe)   # NativeAOT won't list libcoreclr.so\n```\n\n**Quick rule:** `libcoreclr.so` in `/proc/<pid>/maps` → CoreCLR. No `libcoreclr.so` → NativeAOT.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Configure crash dumps\n\n### If CoreCLR\n\nSet environment variables **before** launching the app:\n\n```bash\n# Enable automatic crash dumps via CoreCLR's built-in support\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 4 = Full heap dump (1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\nmkdir -p /var/dumps\n```\n\nAlternatively, use the **OS-level** `core_pattern`:\n\n```bash\n# System-wide kernel core dumps\necho '/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\nulimit -c unlimited   # must be set in the app's shell\n```\n\n### If NativeAOT\n\nNativeAOT does **not** have the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` mechanism (no CoreCLR runtime). You must rely on **OS-level core dumps**:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Configure kernel core pattern\necho '/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# 2. Remove core size limit for the process\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# 3. (Optional) If using systemd, disable its coredump handler or configure it\n# To use systemd-coredump instead:\n#   coredumpctl list   — to view dumps\n#   coredumpctl dump <PID> -o /var/dumps/core.out  — to extract\n```\n\n### Make it persistent (either runtime)\n\n```bash\n# Persist core_pattern across reboots\necho 'kernel.core_pattern = /var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /etc/sysctl.d/90-coredumps.conf\nsudo sysctl --system\n\n# Persist ulimit — add to /etc/security/limits.conf or the systemd unit:\n#   [Service]\n#   LimitCORE=infinity\n```\n\n---\n\n## TL;DR\n\n| | CoreCLR | NativeAOT |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Detection** | `libcoreclr.so` in maps | No `libcoreclr.so` |\n| **Best option** | `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1` | Kernel `core_pattern` |\n| **Analysis tool** | `dotnet-dump analyze` | `gdb` / `lldb` |","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"970bdde1-0e12-45c8-807a-3e8074261ae1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine. That's expected since this is just a workspace, not the user's actual server. Let me provide guidance on how to determine the runtime and configure dumps accordingly.","outputTokens":979},"id":"9e2c2ad5-24d3-44ad-ad67-b97e0d8c50bc","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:10:15.226Z","parentId":"001f5b1d-c038-4e34-9a34-7ed252b6fe85"}
